## 1. `grep` — Search for Patterns

`grep` stands for **Global Regular Expression Print**

It searches for a pattern in a file or input and prints matching lines.

### Syntax
```bash
grep [options] "pattern" filename
```

### Common Options

| Option | Meaning | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `-c` | count matching lines | `grep -c "ERROR" file.log` |
| `-i` | case insensitive | `grep -i "error" file.log` |
| `-v` | invert — show non-matching lines | `grep -v "INFO" file.log` |
| `-n` | show line numbers | `grep -n "ERROR" file.log` |
| `-r` | search recursively in directories | `grep -r "ERROR" /var/logs/` |
| `-l` | show only filenames that match | `grep -l "ERROR" *.log` |
| `-w` | match whole word only | `grep -w "ERR" file.log` |
| `-A 2` | show 2 lines after match | `grep -A 2 "ERROR" file.log` |
| `-B 2` | show 2 lines before match | `grep -B 2 "ERROR" file.log` |

### Examples

```bash
# Count how many ERROR lines
grep -c "ERROR" sample.log

# Show ERROR lines with line numbers
grep -n "ERROR" sample.log

# Case insensitive search
grep -i "error" sample.log     # matches ERROR, error, Error

# Show lines that are NOT INFO
grep -v "INFO" sample.log

# Search in all .log files
grep -r "ERROR" /var/log/

# Show 2 lines around each ERROR for context
grep -A 2 -B 2 "ERROR" sample.log
```

