## 2. `uniq` — Filter Duplicate Lines

`uniq` removes or counts **consecutive duplicate lines**.

> **Important:** Input must be sorted first! `uniq` only compares adjacent lines.

### Syntax
```bash
uniq [options] filename
```

### Common Options

| Option | Meaning | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `-c` | count occurrences | `sort file | uniq -c` |
| `-d` | show only duplicate lines | `sort file | uniq -d` |
| `-u` | show only unique lines | `sort file | uniq -u` |
| `-i` | case insensitive | `sort file | uniq -i` |

### Examples

```bash
# Always sort before uniq!
sort sample.log | uniq           # remove duplicates
sort sample.log | uniq -c        # count each unique line
sort sample.log | uniq -d        # show only duplicates
sort sample.log | uniq -u        # show only non-duplicates
```

### Why sort first?

```bash
# File content:
apple
banana
apple       ← duplicate but not adjacent!

# Without sort — uniq misses it!
uniq file
apple
banana
apple       ← not removed!

# With sort — uniq catches it!
sort file | uniq
apple
banana      ✅ duplicate removed!
```

### Real world usage — find most frequent IP:

```bash
awk '{print $4}' sample.log | sort | uniq -c | sort -rn -k1
```

Step by step:
1. `awk '{print $4}'` — extract IPs
2. `sort` — sort them so duplicates are adjacent
3. `uniq -c` — count each IP
4. `sort -rn -k1` — sort by count highest first

