## 3. Exit Codes — Why We Need Them

Every command in Linux returns an **exit code** when it finishes.

| Exit Code | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `0` | ✅ Success |
| `1` | ❌ General error |
| `2` | ❌ Misuse of command |
| `127` | ❌ Command not found |

### Why exit codes matter?

When scripts are used in automation, other scripts or systems need to know if your script **succeeded or failed** — they can't read your echo messages, but they CAN read exit codes!

```bash
# Example: backup script runs health check first
./health_check.sh
if [ $? -eq 0 ]; then
    ./backup.sh       # only backup if health check passed!
fi
```

### How to check exit code

```bash
# Always use echo $? — never just $?
./myscript.sh
echo $?       # ✅ correct

./myscript.sh
$?            # ❌ wrong — bash tries to run the exit code as a command!
```

### Setting exit codes in your script

```bash
exit 0    # success
exit 1    # failure
exit 2    # misuse
```

### Real world example

```bash
#!/bin/bash
error_count=$(grep -c "ERROR" $1)

if [ $error_count -gt 3 ]; then
    echo "Too many errors!"
    exit 1       # signal failure to calling script/system
fi

echo "All good!"
exit 0           # signal success
```

