## 4. if / elif / else Blocks

### Basic Syntax

```bash
if [ condition ]; then
    # do something
elif [ condition ]; then
    # do something else
else
    # default
fi
```

> Always remember:
> - Space inside `[ ]` — `[ $x -gt 3 ]` not `[$x -gt 3]`
> - `fi` closes the if block
> - `then` after condition

### Numeric Comparison Operators

| Operator | Meaning | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `-eq` | equal to | `[ $a -eq $b ]` |
| `-ne` | not equal to | `[ $a -ne $b ]` |
| `-gt` | greater than | `[ $a -gt 3 ]` |
| `-ge` | greater than or equal | `[ $a -ge 3 ]` |
| `-lt` | less than | `[ $a -lt 3 ]` |
| `-le` | less than or equal | `[ $a -le 3 ]` |

### String Comparison Operators

| Operator | Meaning | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `==` | equal | `[ "$a" == "hello" ]` |
| `!=` | not equal | `[ "$a" != "hello" ]` |
| `-z` | string is empty | `[ -z "$a" ]` |
| `-n` | string is not empty | `[ -n "$a" ]` |

### File Check Operators

| Operator | Meaning | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `-f` | file exists | `[ -f "file.txt" ]` |
| `-d` | directory exists | `[ -d "/home" ]` |
| `-r` | file is readable | `[ -r "file.txt" ]` |
| `-w` | file is writable | `[ -w "file.txt" ]` |
| `-x` | file is executable | `[ -x "script.sh" ]` |

### Examples

```bash
# Numeric comparison
if [ $error_count -gt 3 ]; then
    echo "Too many errors!"
fi

# elif example
if [ $error_count -eq 0 ]; then
    echo "No errors!"
elif [ $error_count -le 3 ]; then
    echo "Some errors but acceptable"
else
    echo "Too many errors!"
fi

# String check
if [ "$name" == "admin" ]; then
    echo "Welcome admin!"
fi

# Check if file exists
if [ -f "sample.log" ]; then
    echo "Log file found!"
else
    echo "Log file missing!"
    exit 1
fi

# Check if argument is empty
if [ -z "$1" ]; then
    echo "Usage: ./script.sh filename"
    exit 1
fi
```

### Combining conditions

```bash
# AND — both must be true
if [ $error_count -gt 3 ] && [ $warn_count -gt 5 ]; then
    echo "Critical state!"
fi

# OR — either must be true
if [ $error_count -gt 3 ] || [ $warn_count -gt 5 ]; then
    echo "Something is wrong!"
fi
```

